Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1Although a big change, I think it is safe. Only documents created outside of LibreOffice should currently be able to create document like this.  Plus, the ODF spec says it should be honoured anyway, if it is defined.The downside is that now the document will display properly, but if someone tries to edit those settings (and perhaps only GO to any format dialog, and then hit OK instead of cancel), the layout will reset to zero padding. Basically, we get read-only compatibility in 5.3, where before we had no compatibility at all.

Patch Set 1:Urk - using virtual inheritance for all of the OutputDevice ref and unref calls ... like this:class VCL_DLLPUBLIC OutputDevice : public virtual VclReferenceBaseI assume that this will then put all those nice previously in-lined, and optimize-able out mnRefCnt++ and -- pairs behind virtual function calls. Patch Set 1:> > However I decided against it, since reading configuration on > every repaint brings some performance penalty >  > I see, just wondered if the performance penalty is really severe or > not. I didn't observe any slowdown myself, but that doesn't mean that other people wouldn't, who knows what they do with their office :) e.g. this blogpost explains why are frequent configuration readings a bad idea: https://mmohrhard.wordpress.com/2015/10/07/short-update-about-the-performance-testing/ > What we want then would be to derive utl::ConfigurationListener and > provide a suitable ConfigurationChanged( ::utl::ConfigurationBroadcaster*, > sal_uInt32 ), > as in Calc's ScModule (ScModule::ConfigurationChanged() in > sc/source/ui/app/scmod.cxx) > and Writer's SwModule (SwModule::ConfigurationChanged in > sw/source/uibase/app/apphdl.cxx), etc. > Right?Aye, that's exactly what I meant :)

Patch Set 2:So, reverting it will reintroduce those two bugs this "fixes".This is one of these very common situations in Calc where, 1) the feature expectation is not very clear, 2) there is no test, 3) no code doc indicating how the code should behave, and 4) an attempt to fix stuff will get met with "this is wrong, please revert". ;-)Frustrating...

Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1visually, LO round-trips this just fine, and has no problems with it. Only MS-Word indicates any issues, so no unit test is possible.The regression causing this issue covers an oddball situation already, so just avoiding the whole thing within a table seems like the best solution.I never could figure out what is ultimately causing the problem, because dealing with cells is very complicated. I'm pretty sure it was related to the anchor (position 26) being past the end of the string portions(0-23,24,25).  But even the delay of the first portion caused the +Fkp error, and nothing I tried stopped the cell "Enter Personal Websites  " from getting mangled except for completely avoiding postponement.

Patch Set 5: Code-Review-2(1 comment)I advise against hardcoding specific services. Especially when they are only available in a small subset of languages.Letting special cases creep in like the one in flagged in the comment is even worse.Instead of hardcoding the ask site, make it a generic "find help online" or similar, that links to the domain specifically created for those kind of links: http://hub.libreoffice.org/something.That in turn can then redirect to language specific resources. (either redirect directly to askbot or show a overview page, depending on language. That then can be maintained/updated independently from LO (you cannot change the hardcoded URLs in a released version of LO after all)so again:* make it a generic page instead (not "Questions and Answers" but something like "Get help online" or something similar)* all URLs in LibreOffice itself should be http://hub.libreoffice.org/something ones.definite -2 because of the special handling of locales, without it it would still be a fat -1 from me

Patch Set 5:it looks like we still owe you some answers to your questions :)the only way to build with python 2 is to use --enable-python=system and set PYTHON, PYTHON_CFLAGS and PYTHON_LIBS variables manually to the right values, i.e. PYTHON_CFLAGS=`pkg-config --cflags python` PYTHON_LIBS=`pkg-config --libs python` before running autogen.sh(this is deliberately inconvenient so that newbies don't do it by accident)the only easy way to run all python tests is "make check" but that will run all tests, the faster way is to run every PythonTest_foo that exists manually via "make PythonTest_foo".unfortunately it often happens that broken commits are pushed to master and that will break your jenkins build here too if your change is based on the broken master, probably that's what happened here in some cases.

Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1Love it - thanks for the swamp draining Markus ! =) I guess my lingering concern is what happens when we have SEH enabled code that catches a SEGV vs. normal code - does that mean we get various exceptions thrown out of eg. OGL drivers that are compiled with this option (?) etc. anyhow - moving closer to the Linux case sounds like a good idea to me for window stability =)Thanks.

Patch Set 2:> Love it - thanks for the swamp draining Markus ! =) I guess my > lingering concern is what happens when we have SEH enabled code > that catches a SEGV vs. normal code - does that mean we get various > exceptions thrown out of eg. OGL drivers that are compiled with > this option (?) etc. anyhow - moving closer to the Linux case > sounds like a good idea to me for window stability =) >  > Thanks.So EHs only affects whether we catch the SEH or not. It does not affect how other code handles it. Of course if we get a lot of SEH excepions from outside of our control that are currently caught in one of the catch all handlers we are going to crash a lot.EHs has basically two effects on the code. catch(...) will not catch SEH exceptions and there is no stack nwinding and destructor calls going to be for SEH exceptions.I think both are fine in our code. The case that some external part is handling SEH with EHa should not concern us as if we get a SEH from that cod ewe will just crash and if that code handles it we are not going to see it anyway.

Patch Set 5:> Just curious, what's the benefit of genLang, compared to the > current l10ntools, after the kill-sdf branch was merged? >  > See http://libreoffice.hu/2012/11/27/featurekillsdf-branch-merged/ > for the background.the kill sdf was a very good thing, but it did not change the tools or the method. The "save" method in the old tools was rewritten to save .pot files.genLang "reinvents" the tools in a C++ fashion, making it more maintainable. You can however argue, that since the old tools work, why change it. The best reason for that is to move away from the central "make translations" that runs find over the source tree, and into adding the files to the local makefiles (e.g. define ui files like you define cxx files).

Patch Set 4:> > RGB happens to be defined by wingdi.h and leaks from multiple > > places. This was the easiest/simplest fix; to undef it where it > > conflicts. For other cases it was enough to undef them in > postwin.h > > and make sure it's called after including windows headers. >  > But wouldn't it be better to handle undef'ing RGB in postwin.h, and > make sure any include of wingdi.h is wrapped in prewin/postwin.h? I tried that. And can give it another try. But it would require a much bigger change, obviously. The main problem is that wingdi.h is actually included from other windows headers too. So we can't fully control when it's included. But can give it another shot and narrow it down further. In fact, I spent hours trying to find what file includes the conflicting values to create this patch. > The current fix allows workdir/CustomTarget/officecfg/registry/officecfg/Office/Common.hxx > to be included, but if a source file happens to first include that > officecfg/Office/Common.hxx, then include wingdi.h, and later wants > to acutally use the struct RGB from Common.hxx, it still runs into > a problem.Well, that would be be a problem _only_ if wingdi.h was already included _before_ Office/Common.h, and in that case the build would fail because the macro would conflict with the declaration of RGB (my patch avoids this situation).However, if wingdi.h was _not_ included at the point of #undef RGB, then nothing bad would happen if it is included afterwards. Unless I missed something, I don't see how there would still be a problem, as wingdi.h will define RGB without issue.I should add that I hated this particular line of my patch. I share your view that it's best avoided altogether. But I couldn't find a better solution. Will try again though.

Patch Set 1:To elaborate on how to amend a patch: The trick here is preserving the same Change-Id of the commit message, so that Gerrit recognizes it should be on the same thread. Locally, you do a new commit, then you do `git rebase -i HEAD~2' to squash that with the previous commit. Then you push and Gerrit will detect your updated squashed commit as a new version (or ÔÇ£patch setÔÇØ) without creating a new thread. Hope this helps!

Patch Set 1:> To elaborate on how to amend a patch: The trick here is preserving > the same Change-Id of the commit message, so that Gerrit recognizes > it should be on the same thread. Locally, you do a new commit, then > you do `git rebase -i HEAD~2' to squash that with the previous > commit.Git commit --amend is a much easier way to do that.iow checkout your gerrit patchdo the modificationscommit them using --amendgit push origin HEAD:refs/for/master Then you push and Gerrit will detect your updated squashed > commit as a new version (or ÔÇ£patch setÔÇØ) without creating a new > thread. Hope this helps!

Patch Set 3:Replying to myself: Yeah, they are.USING_X11 is TRUE when we are building for a platform that uses X11, and we haven't used the --without-x option. with_x is "no" when we have used the switch --without-x (which used to be called --enable-headless), and that de facto has been developed only for platforms where X11 *could* be used. So USING_X11!=TRUE turns out to be equivalent to with_x==no. Unless I miss something;)In theory one could also imagine building a LibreOffice for Windows or OS X that would not use any display-oriented APIs, but that would be fairly pointless, as that functionality is always present in the OS anyway. It isn't like Linux, where some people think it is useful to have installations without any X11 stuff.

I made attachments for both tdf89872 and tdf88547 containing a bit of both types of function calls.These attachments give the same result in Excel as in Calc (with this patch set).I have not tested Excel with inline text arrays like {"1","3","4"}; my patch will accept this.IMHO the sort of patch you suggest will keep a difference between Excel and Calc and therefor will lead to a bug report sooner or later. Patch Set 3:the A?=B syntax is a way in Makefileto doif A has no value then A=Belse keep A's valuethat way one can export A= before the invocation of makeand the user value is honored.seehttps://www.gnu.org/software/make/manual/html_node/Setting.html#index-_003f_003d-1The proper way is to run the pch script from Makefile, in which case A would be set naturally with the appropriate value.Note our makefile support the target 'cmd' for that very purpose:make cmd cmd="./bin/update_pch.sh [..]"which avoid the evil use of get_config_variables

Patch Set 3:When designing the framework, we had two basic ideas:- interesting document models are easier to be loaded from some format, than building them from code- checking an in-memory document model is reasonably easy (usually by using the UNO API), at least easier than asserting a written file (think of manually checking a binary .doc result)That's why for export tests, we do an import->export->import sequence. That ensures that the doc. models can be still stored in a file, allows asserting the result using the UNO API, and still export problems are detected. (I'm just re-stating what's in sw/qa/extras/README, just in case for some reason that file is not clear.) Hopefully this makes it clear how export tests are done. :-)Regarding loosing data during import/export: sure, sometimes that's necessary when e.g. our numbering types and MSO's numbering types do not match. In your case, the provided tests passed just fine when also the exporter got included in the chain, that's why I changed that. As long as it passes, it's safe to change, and it ensures that your export improvements won't break in the future silently. ;-)

Patch Set 9: Code-Review-1I still don't see how you expect HAVE_POSIX_MEMALIGN and HAVE_MEMALIGN to propagate to the compilations. (Of course, you don't notice if/that they don't in your compilations, as you care only for the cases where they are not defined.)The OOo/LO codebase is full of delusions of grandeur and misleading names for various bits and pieces. Don't take the "system abstraction layer" expansion of the "sal" acronym too literally.Of course want it to be easy to remove your code at some point. This codebase is 20 years old now, and I expect (fear?) that it will be around after 20 years still, too. Do even you expect PowerPC Macs and OS X 10.5 to be around any more at that point in time?

Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1I don't think this is good.  If we offer a general-purpose, low-level rtl_allocateAlignedMemory that promises to return aligned memory, it should not be able to silently return non-aligned memory.  (If you're confident that it is OK for your 10.5 port to silently return non-aligned memory, then please make this conditional exactly on that 10.5 port.)

Patch Set 3:"can you please suggest solution for Darwin/OSX where are no posix_memalign nor memalign?"  Recent OS X does have posix_memalign, so it apparently only is a problem for the 10.5 port.  As I wrote, "If you're confident that it is OK for your 10.5 port [...], then please make this conditional exactly on that 10.5 port," i.e., I'd suggest using the usual MAC_OS_X_VERSION_MAX_ALLOWED < 1060 instead of a newly introduced HAVE_POSIX_MEMALIGN."Also, don't forget that there're another platforms where posix_memalign is not available."  Which relevant ones are that?  And they potentially offer some similar functionality already that we could use, like in the Android case."When this memory.c has been introduced? Why? For what purpose?"  See git log.

Patch Set 1: Do not mergePlease try to provide atomic changes instead of all-in-one commit.First, you are changing minimum SDK version we are not interested in ÔÇö┬áthere is a sweet ICS future, it is more wise to move forward instead of backward. Second, changing target SDK should be supported via build servers to not fail. Third, we are not interested at moment in switching from ABS to ABC because LO Android port uses ABS anyway and, again, this should be supported via build servers. Fourth, SettingsActivity after your change wouldnÔÇÖt have an action bar on pre-Honeycomb versions.I agree with you that ABS ÔåÆ ABC migration makes sense but there is a *really low* percentage of users using Gingerbread. It makes a very little sense for me to swap dependencies for things that just work for platform version which *potentially* could be dropped.

Patch Set 1:> Please try to provide atomic changes instead of all-in-one commit.This is an atomic commit. Splitting that up would result in unbuildable project/mix of abs and android support lib. Not what you want.And did you even bother to look at the patch? All those changes are trivial, basically replacing "Sherlock" with "Compat" or similar> First, you are changing minimum SDK version we are not interested in ÔÇö there is a sweet ICS future, it is more wise to move forward instead of backward.Changing the minimum version doesn't impact use of new ICS features at all. That's what the support libraries are for. ActionBarSherlock previously, and the default android support library in the proposal.You fail to mention what ICS features are lost by that, so please elaborate. And of course one doesn't need to lower it - but why artificially limiting the usable devices when there is no reason?> Second, changing target SDK should be supported via build servers to not fail.No idea what you mean by that. Target SDK is the version that is definitely supported, i.e. in this case the version that runs on a device I personally own, did personally test with. But again, no biggie to leave that at present values.> Third, we are not interested at moment in switching from ABS to ABCWho is "we"?> because LO Android port uses ABS anyway and,How is the LO Android port related to the Impress Remote? The remote(s) have already been decoupled translation wise, release-schedule wise, so I fail to see how the remote is bound to the Android port.Again the changes are small, the android support libraries stack up easily to support newer features.You mentioned that newer versions have nice features and you'd rather drop support for older devices: using the android support libs makes that easy. In Fact the ABS one already used the v4 support library itself.> again, this should be supported via build servers.And again no idea what you mean by that. If you mean it should be buildable by ant/using the makefiles and not by using Eclipse, you should see that I also updated the makefile.I didn't bother to add a check whether the v7 support library has been installed on the machine, as it is not built as part of LO anyway, and the error message will be pretty obvious in that case....If you insist, I can also add configure checks. Or do the easy way as with the abs and check it into the repo.> Fourth, SettingsActivity after your change wouldnÔÇÖt have an action bar on pre-Honeycomb versions.It will.> I agree with you that ABS ÔåÆ ABC migration makes sense but there is a *really low* percentage of users using Gingerbread.I didn't change it because I wanted to lower the minimumSDK, that was just the result of the lint check that this is the minimum that the code uses.> It makes a very little sense for me to swap dependencies for things that just work for platform version which *potentially* could be dropped.I don't care about the minimum SDK, so don't fixate on that.  I did swap dependencies for the contrary, to make it easier to extend later with new features. Even the author of the ABS wrote that ABS has done its job, that with the android support lib v7 there is no reason to use ABS anymore. That of course doesn't mean one should swap components, never change a running system yadda,yadda, but the remote is small, the change as a whole is small, so it is (IMHO) a sensible thing to do.You also state on the one-hand pre honeycomb (aka gingerbread) would look different, but on the other hand you're willing to just drop support for gingerbread completely. So I fail to see how this then is a concern regarding this patch.

Patch Set 2:While I appreciate that you took your time to comment on my patches, I cannot take your comments seriously.In the other patch you say it's fine to completely ignore the interaction guidelines (not enable BT without user's consent), but here you insist that a design that was introduced on newer devices must be enforced on older devices (that you're happy to not even support at all).You also fail to explain why just keeping strings that are meant to always displayed upppercase in all-caps in the resources is no solution.

Patch Set 2:> In the other patch you say it's fine to completely ignore the interaction guidelines (not enable BT without user's consent), but here you insist that a design that was introduced on newer devices must be enforced on older devices (that you're happy to not even support at all).I see this as a visual design and UX. The visual design is defined. If Android has the Roboto font developers should consider using it instead of Comic Sans. If the whole platform uses uppercase headers developers should consider to implement it as well. On other hand the UX of Bluetooth interaction has a kind of broken state ÔÇö┬áyes, in perfect world users should enable it themselves, but why there are no dialog for disabling it themselves? Does it make sense to force user to use dialog every time one launches the app? Why user should even care about enabling or disabling Bluetooth at all? IÔÇÖm not trying to reject things I donÔÇÖt want to see or use ÔÇö┬áI try to think about better implementations which cause pleasant experience and not emotions like ÔÇ£oh this dialog againÔÇØ, ÔÇ£again this app causes battery drainÔÇØ.> You also fail to explain why just keeping strings that are meant to always displayed upppercase in all-caps in the resources is no solution.1. It is easier to translate strings when you see simple words instead of WORDS. 2. If in the future the platform remove this headers style we can just tweak the style for the text and not the text for the style.

Patch Set 1:I chose the mingw mailing list entry, because there's a nice compilation of old WINVER defines, which the Microsoft documentation doesn't offer :)And at the moment we need to set WINVER because it has everywhere different values. Or we have hacks like adefd564d07a6e70cc1d9fad8febe5b434511e83 or a9fd489834b63e423d4745f0d71cf15396e3e3eb. At least for fpicker it's relevant because with 0x0501 you wouldn't get the window previews in the taskbar with Vista/7. So we need 0x0600 there, but we can't set it global to the project if we still want to support Windows XP.But you're right, after that commit many of them could be simply dropped.

Patch Set 6:Sorry, I didn't mention it, but yes this does need a make clean. The patch was indeed finished.I didn't wonder about the WIN32_LEAN_AND_MEAN redefinition, because this is how it's done in some other makefiles. Thanks for fixing this.Nice that this finally got into core :)

Patch Set 2:Now the settings are applied globally.And I found out how to use the macros:_WIN32_WINNT sets NTDDI_VERSION and WINVER automatically to the same version.But setting NTDDI_VERSION or WINVER sets only the macro itself.If we want to target Windows XP we need to set _WIN32_WINNT, because otherwise other SDK stuff is still included under Windows 7. But this brings us some kind of dilemma: How do we add features which are added in Windows 7 (like 9a4a84df5406cdcde1f4d23a1cea2b109998f35b)? If we set WINVER globally those features are never activated.One solution could be to check:#ifdef NTDDI_WIN7Works fine, but checks only what is supported by the Windows API (what if Win8 SDK is installed on Win7?).Maybe we should move this to the mailing list.

Patch Set 5:I mean, my understanding is:Previously, the page number offset was a single unsigned integer, where 0 meant "no restart", other values meant a restart with a positive value. This is obviously a problem if you want to have a restart with a zero value.The patch introduces bNumOffsetIsSet to signal if the page number offset is valid, this is a good move. However at other places it also starts to use -1 to signal that the page number offset is valid or not, so now we have two places storing the same info (bNumOffsetIsSet == true or page number offset == -1), which looks redundant.

Patch Set 1:This change is related to columns in text sections, not columns for pages. I guess page columns are not exported to HTML because there is really no generally applicable way of doing that; HTML pages do not have fixed height like pages in Writer do.To test this you need to- Open a new empty Writer document- Choose Insert -> Section- Go to Columns tab and type in a number, 3 for example, click Insert.- now you can see the little grey section markers, paste some long text inside those.- save as HTML, you should end up with a HTML document that has a MULTICOL element that contains the column count both in the old non-standard COLS-attribute and in the new css column-count attribute.PS. I hope this is the right way to respond to the review comment. I'm just trying to learn how to use this Gerrit tool.

Do we actually use the result anywhere?"While we don't appear to be using HAVE_BOOST_UNORDERED_MAP anywhere (so setting it could be removed), we do #include "boost/unordered_map.hxx" in lots of places.  So if the system boost does not support that, we should probably error-out/switch to our boost.Forcing -std=gnu++0x for the check without coordinating that with HAVE_CXX0X (which will determine whether --std=gnu++0x is actually enabled in the build) is not really helpful, though.

Patch Set 1:Wrt. the starvation - actually that was due to the logging; we have so much debugging stuff that it was blocking considerably when writing to the console, making the queue grow.  Without that, all works fine even with the unmodified TileQueue :-)But I worked on the TileQueue too - it seems unnecessary to do all the priority shuffling when inserting, when the prioritization changes with every view switch, and instead do it only when the tile is requested - which seems to work nicely.Wrt. an own queue for tiles - that is exactly the thing that makes the synchronzation hard, as then it is necessary to synchronize between those 2 queues; which in turn kills all the advantage of 2 queues :-)Wrt. PNG compression; if we want to thread it, then let's thread just the compression - that'll make it local, more maintainable, and we can go with as many threads there as we wish (for just the PNG compression piece of code).Wrt. the 342125b8ea - thanks for that!  Unfortunately that again just adds code :-(Either way, please check https://cgit.freedesktop.org/libreoffice/online/log/?h=private/kendy/tilesandcallbacks , I'd really like to get that in...  I've tested it with several people in a session, and it performed pretty well thanks to all your work I was able to build on.

Likely a <number:minutes-unambiguous> element will not make it into the standard.

Patch Set 1:In general, I am personally not that convinced that adding such #ifdef DEBUG_FOO_BAR is that useful. There is a large risk that the code inside those will bit-rot anyway sooner or later. And if this code at some stage needs debugging, it is questionable whether the specific optional debug code that was perhaps useful some time ago will still be useful, or whether one will need to write more complicated or complete debugging code anyway. I would just remove it. But I am not insisting.

Patch Set 2:To summarize what has been discussed on IRC today:I'm not a big fan of encouraging users to use deprecated and insecure protocols (let's be honest, DDE *is* deprecated and insecure). If this is mainly about inserting links with relative paths, maybe your goals could be achieved by using relative references, i.e. =DDE("soffice"; "some/relative/path"; "SheetX.CellY")would become ='some/relative/path'#SheetXCellY'and the development effort could be targeted at implementing some UI and clipboard support for relative references and fixing outstanding relative reference issues (sometimes target doc doesn't update if source doc changes, ~/ path doesn't expand correctly etc.)

Patch Set 1:Hmm, is this only a nice-to-have patch or it makes life really hard on the g-d side if this is not accepted?I'm asking as up to today, we could freely add as many new signals as we wanted to the widget without breaking ABI. However, with your patch, the list of signals become part of the ABI and we limit the number of new signals ever to be added.In other words it's a large cost to support these function pointers -- if possible, it would be really nice to avoid this. The larger the interface we promise to be stable, the harder to make future changes.

Patch Set 2:@tml:Yes, The GCD() function is Calc matches the Excel function, with two notes:-Excel has limits for the size of the arguments (must be less than 2E53), Calc doesn't and never had that limit (neither Calc's own, nor add-in function);-Excel GCD accepts only integer arguments in Excel versions prior to 2007 and accepts floating point arguments since Excel 2007, Calc accepts all numeric arguments (both Calc's own as add-in function).It is quite common for Calc functions to be more tolerant with respect to type and/or numeric value limits than their Excel counterparts.

Patch Set 6:I still don't like introducing a new document-wide UNO setting when we already have a setting in ODF format doing exactly the same ...Anyway, I did some git archaeology and found out that this "Impress always opens on 1st slide" is an artificial restriction imposed by a design document + OOo feature request from 2005 (https://bz.apache.org/ooo/show_bug.cgi?id=50902)Moreover, keyboard accelerator listed therein (Shift-F5) that was supposed to be used to jump to the last edited slide (the one saved as SelectedPage) no longer works, since it is used for different purpose now (start a slideshow from current slide)So I think this restriction (always open on 1st slide, unless the presentation is an embedded OLE object) can nowadays be removed and that should be the way to fix this issue. I.e. removing this 'if ...( SFX_CREATE_MODE_EMBEDDED == pDoc->GetDocSh()->GetCreateMode()' condition when reading SelectedPage setting ... unless it crashes Impress or cause other nasties ...Anyway, I'm adding Thorsten to Cc: to get a second opinion on that ...

(pDrawDoc->GetCurrentPage() )Can you please cherry-pick and try. I don't think we need that import and export code as mentioned in comment 3 on the bug page.Thanks for the letting me know about the variable naming, will fix that.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1So, Markus and I had the same discussion years ago.  The reason why we still keep auto_ptr there was 2 things: 1) make the code exception safe, and 2) ptr_set requires auto_ptr to be passed to be truly exception safe.  2) is a loose requirement and you can also pass a raw pointer to ptr_set (as you noticed).  But your current change is a step backward in terms of 1).The best strategy for this use case is to use o3tl::heap_ptr to replace auto_ptr, and call heap_ptr's release() when passing it to ptr_set.  Then the code remains exception safe and we can get rid of auto_ptr.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2Actually this is not exactly a duplicate.Calc has 2 separate "paste special" dialogs. One is when pasting from system clipboard, and the other is pasting from Calc itself.  This one you are proposing to change is used for the 2nd variant.Try opening a new Calc document, and while nothing is copied, hit Ctrl-Shift-V.  This will bring up the system paste special dialog.  Now, select some cells and Ctrl-C to copy, then Ctrl-Shift-V. This will bring up the Calc paste special dialog.I'm not saying we shouldn't change this wording, but I'm not in favor of calling this "insert contents" which would make less sense than "paste special".

Patch Set 1:Looking good - to readd it to this change, you need to run:git rebase -iThis will take you into your favourite text editor. Take the latter change (the last line) and where it says "pick" change this to "s". This "squashes" the commit into the previous commit. Save and exit the editor. At this point, you might be taken into another editor session, remove all the comments (and Gerrit changeset ID) from the commit you just squashed. Then save and exit again. It should rebase the changes into the first commit with the first commit message. Then push the change to gerrit again as you did last time.

Patch Set 1: (4 inline comments)1) IMHO the negative year fix should go in independently of the time zone issue.3) Why should DateTimeRange contain only one time zone, as opposed to one for   the start value and one for the end value?3) You add time zone information to dates. I don't know the meaning of that.   What would it mean, how would it behave, what would it be used for?   For example, naively, one would think that combining a date with a time,   one would get a datetime. How does one get a datetime by combining   2003-05-17+05 with 23:00-06?   FWIW, SQL does not define a DATE WITH TIME ZONE type.4) I have my doubts about time-zoned time without a date.   How do you convert 20:00+00 to time zone +10?   Just "wrap around" modulo 24, i.e. make it 06:00+10?   If you answer yes to that question (that is, always compute modulo 24),   then what is the difference between 06:00+11 and 06:00-13?   The difference only makes sense if one speaks of dates...   Which says that timezones don't make sense unless we know at what date   to apply them.   FWIW, SQL defines a TIME WITH TIME ZONE TYPE, *but* here's what   the PostgreSQL documentation has to say about it:   The type time with time zone is defined by the SQL standard, but the definition exhibits properties which lead to questionable usefulness. In most cases, a combination of date, time, timestamp without time zone, and timestamp with time zone should provide a complete range of date/time functionality required by any application.   (...) we recommend using date/time types that contain both date and time when using time zones. We do not recommend using the type time with time zone (though it is supported by PostgreSQL for legacy applications and for compliance with the SQL standard).I have half a mind to add timezone *only* to DateTime and DateTimeRange,not to Date and not to Time. Note that this would more-or-less eliminateall conversion problems, and "unlock" the scenario "don't add timezoneto structs, but convert everything to UTC", since conversion of datetimevalues across timezones is AFAIK well-defined. "Convert everything to UTC"is SQL's behaviour; in SQL all non-timezoned values are assumed to be atlocal time and a date is converted to the timestamp "same date at time 00:00".Alternative approach to your "isTimezoned": have a separate struct "DateTimeTZ"?Your "isTimezoned" flag should IMHO be called "isUTC".Do we actually *need* *any* "unknown timezone / local timezone" value in memory?We could just make some assumption (UTC or local TZ) on import/parse/readand store only UTC in memory. Oh, but it would be convenient for our APIs to havethe capacity to take implicitly-localTZ values, yes.If we go the "assume that values without explicit time zone are in local time" route,then that flag should be called "isUTC".So, I've spoken of what SQL does as a reference;https://wiki.documentfoundation.org/Development/LibreOffice4#Changes_deferred_until_4.1mentions XMLSchema-2. Let's see what it does for another reference: - It (optionally) timezones everything: date, time and datetime. - I don't see a datetimerange in it. - It understands a date as a 24-hour interval   (a DateTimeRange, from date 00:00:00.00000000 to 23:59:59.999999999 for most days,    that is except for leap seconds),    while SQL seems to consider it more like an instant, time 00:00 at that day. - A value without timezone is "unknown timezone" and not comparable   to a value with timezone, but on the other hand, section 3.2.7 also calls   untimezoned values "local values", which supports the idea that they are   "local time". But "local time" is unspecified in an interchange file format,   because the file may move from one timezone to the other.   In SQL, everything is convertible/comparable because each session has an   active "local timezone" which is used for all untimezoned values.Pragmatically, how close to XMLSchema-2 do we need to be?1) Is there any part of ODF/OOXML/any other format where we need to import   or export a date with timezone?2) Is there any part of ODF/OOXML/any other format where we need to import   or export a time (*not* datetime) with timezone?3) Is there any part of ODF/OOXML/any other format where there can be a   datetime with timezone OR a datetime without timezone and the difference   has some semantic significance (other than "interpret value without   timezone in this timezone").4) Is there any part of ODF/OOXML/any other format where we need to import   or export a datetime value without timezone and preserve unmodified as   without timezone?   The kind of scenario I'm thinking of is:   We read a datetime value without timezone from some file, and the file   does not give a context that tells us what time zone to interpret that in,   the user changes stuff, but not the part with that datetime value,   *and* when saving the file again, we need to write back the same value,   as opposed to say the UTC value of that datetime-in-local-timezone   or the same datetime value with local-timezone affixed.5) Is there any part of ODF/OOXML/any other format where we need to import   or export a datetime value without timezone, do changes on it and preserve   it as without timezone?   The kind of scenario I'm thinking of is:   We read a datetime value without timezone from some file, and the file   does not give a context that tells us what time zone to interpret that in,   the user e.g. tells us "add one hour to that datetime value",   *and* when saving the file again, we need to write back the new value   as untimezoned, as opposed to say the UTC value of that   datetime-in-local-timezone or the same datetime value with local-timezone   affixed.

Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)> In lcl_ConvertTimeZone() in sax/source/tools/converter.cxx, > you are attempting to convert times between timezones. > I don't think this can be done safely without access to a > DST (Daylight Savings Time) database. It depends what you call "timezone". If it is something like "Europe/Amsterdam", that is "the time in Amsterdam", then yes, DST matters. But here, the notion of timezone is just an offset from UTC. That is, we consider that Amsterdam *changes* timezone twice per year. In this case, sure, we can freely / safely convert, we just have to subtract the offset.

Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit thisIn general, such ifdeffed-out code should not be removed just blindly, but one should check for how long it has been ifdeffed out, and whether there is any comment indicating it is soemthing a still active developer intends to get back to, etc.In this case, I think this code might well be useful, if only we had somebody who was working on this part of the code and was interested in this self-check functionality.(Personally I have no idea what a "job" or "job URL" is.)There is a comment in joburl.cxx that says: "It's used for internal purposes only and never a part of a legal product. Use it for testing and debug only!" so I think it's clear that the intent is that you #define ENABLE_COMPONENT_SELF_CHECK only in your own work copy while working on this code, and that such a #define never gets into version control.Now, another question is then whether we have anybody who knows what this code does, and is interested in debugging and developing it. Would it be better to test DBG_UTIL instead of ENABLE_COMPONENT_SELF_CHECK, to at least make sure the code still compiles (in a --enable-dbgutil build) and doesn't break at run-time?SOme discussion on the mailing list needed IMHO.

Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit thisHi Mathias,first thanks for your patch. It is great start; Well, it does some non-standard things. I suggest to re-shufle it a bit :-)1. You already mentioned that you were unsure about    downloading the files inside configure. I suggest to   do it using the download script.   You might already see the many @FILENAME@ entries in   ooo.lst.in. They are optional. If you do not define such    variable in configure, it will be empty in the generated    ooo.lst file and it will not be downloaded.2. If you use download, it will get the files into the   $TARFILE_LOCATION instead of $SRC_ROOT/moz/zipped.      I suggest to modify the related makefiles in "moz"    module to find the .zip archives in $TARFILE_LOCATION   Note that this approach follows the current trends.   In the past, we copied many 3rd party tarballs into   the related build subdirectories. We do not longer   do it.
